Ups & downs. 

The world around us tends to tell us life should be free of struggles & that hardship is a sign of something being wrong with us. 

The truth is going through hard things is a part of the human experience.

While I hold very real excitement around marrying someone I love so deeply I also experience the very real pain of family relationships not being as God intended them to be. While I get the absolute gift of planning my dream wedding I also experience the stress of money flying out of my account faster than ever.

Daily I have to juggle running a company, being a fiancé, seeking spiritual growth, planning a major life event & all the other things that get thrown my way.

I think to acknowledge that the human experience includes both struggles and victories shatters the narrative that an easy  life is the goal.

The real human experience isn’t void of struggles. It’s actually really appropriate for hard times to take place. 

Not because anything is wrong but because that is to be human.

dark & light. 

I felt a nudge to read my journal from Dec 31, 2020 about the year ahead & reading it back absolutely blew my mind. 

I first wrote about how I felt 2021 would be a shedding of skin, there would be an emerging & how it felt vulnerable yet right. 

I wrote about how I felt as if old things, old habits, old me would melt away & I would emerge as myself. 

I saw me and God standing behind a curtain & God saying you got this & the we pulled the curtain together and got to experience the fullness of being seen. 

I saw my writings here being more honest than ever & how I would find a spot light here to share my real self. 

As we draw closer to another year ending I look back on my naive self writing a narrative for this year with absolutely no idea what was ahead. 

I see now what all the shedding old skin and layers meant. I see how breaking old habits served me better than I could have known it would a year ago. 

I see how much I as myself have emerged for the past as more me than ever before. 

It’s all so clear on the other side. 

I guess I feel for those in the unclear moments (as I was a year ago to all that is now clear). I feel as though this revelation of clarity coming isn’t just for me. 

For anyone who feels lost, unsure, confused, disoriented, or just plain over it — I encourage you to dig your heels into God in this moment. Ask him to tell you what is ahead. As crazy as it sounds write it down. 

His master plans do tend to sound a bit crazy at first but on the other side they are better than you could have ever asked for.

humbled. 

In counseling recently we talked about allowing my emotions to happen. 

Growing up I saw emotions take hold of people and I chose to run down the opposite path. I boxed up my emotions and used control to silence them. 

I learned through years of disconnected relationships that  I could no longer keep my emotions silenced and claim I wanted deep relationships. 

Through lots of time with my counselor I’m getting the hang of letting emotions happen. 

Because I’m so new to this I find myself like a child in this time. I make mistakes, misplace emotions, & don’t handle things perfectly. 

The odd part is that I’m proud of myself still. I’m proud that I’m learning. I’m proud that I’m being refined. I’m proud that I’m taking accountability repeatedly. 

It’s a wild ride trying to build skills you seem to have missed the boat on. I’m doing it though & it’s tough but worth it.

Sip Sip Hooray @itsblume has blends for this holiday! 

Lots been going on on the home front. Got in a car accident, Spent time with people I love, secured some main wedding vendors, & asked a few bridesmaids into the wedding party. 

With all the hustle and bustle of the holidays I am sitting back to write this post with absolute astonishment in how good god is. 

Amidst all the hard things & stress he has this gentle way of calming all to remind me how grounded I am. 

This season hold the people you love tight, splurge on a self treat here & there, & most of all tuck away to spend time hearing god’s heart for this time.

Unprocessed Thoughts. 

There’s been a lot on my mind lately in regards to church and faith and God and all that.

There are these little left over pockets of pain from past experiences coming to the surface and asking for my attention. 

A past version of myself would have tried to shove that down. A recent version of myself would have tried to compassion them away. 

Today’s version of myself is asking the emotion to unveil itself to me in a deeper way. 

It’s an odd experience to have pain come up and to go against all my self protective reflexes in hopes to be present with it. 

I’m learning a lot from this though. I’m learning that abundant grace can at times lead to pain. I’m learning that not enough grace leaves you alone in the end. I’m learning that the perfect amount of grace isn’t a human quality to have — it’s a freely given from God. 

Lots & lots to learn.

Cheers. 

A few years back I chose to leave a church after about a year of full immersion there. 

In my time there I experienced a lot of scary behaviors. One of which was the call for all attendees to stop going to other churches and to only engage with our small community.

I was told that other Christians were less than our community and that associating with them would be destructive to my faith.

When leaving this church I entered into an incredibly lonely season.  I had no one. I walked away from all my friendships in order to “protect my faith.” 

I remember daily sitting down to my journal crying & begging God to put good people in my life. 

It was lonely and scary and overwhelming. 

After years of that prayer I see these photos and am brought to tears. 

I’m brought tears because of the incredible answer to prayer that I see. 

If you’ve ever been in a lonely season or even currently are in one — 

Please don’t lose hope. There are good people out there! 

Lonely times are so hard but as someone who gets the absolute honor to be around people of such incredible character after a really hard season of loneliness — I promise it will get better. 

Hold on & reach out!

Wedding on film. 

Before I was engaged I heard that the engagement season and wedding planning season  are both hard, stressful, & overwhelming. 

From my experience though “wedding planning stress” isn’t the actual planning at all. It’s more so the relational dynamics, opinions of others, & opportunity for growth. 

Those are 100% real and I do have to deal with those almost daily. For that I recommend therapy haha

But I do wish for those out there who are pre-engaged or engaged to be a voice that this time doesn’t have to be all hard. 

My experience has been so fun, light, & joy filled. I fall more in love with my fiancé with each passing second, I get to see my wedding fall into place more each day, & I get to receive help from people around me. 

I’m savoring every second of a season that I will never get again. 

Yes, hard moments happen but that’s life. Yes, relationship dynamics are difficult but better to flush that out before marriage. Yes, the money part is challenging but if being refined is the goal then you’re practicing before you need the tools. 

I have so much more to say on this — even tips for how to have a season you look back on and love! 

We’ve got plenty of time to get all those out though!

Seasoned. 

In just about a week I turn 25. 

Part of me is excited to close the chapter of 24 while some part of me feels that 25 is a bigger, more mature, & older year than ever before. 

For most of my life I felt that I never reflected my birthday. I never felt the number was  appropriate to my life or personality. 

I was too busy taking care of my parents to truly feel 12 or 16 or even 20… lately I’ve started to approach a sort of settling into my age. 

Growing up I remember telling my dad that at 24 I felt like I would meet the one and maybe even get engaged. I remember even journaling for years about 24 being a major year for me. 

All turned out to be unbelievably accurate to my current life. 

So to close a chapter to all that and begin to catch up with myself in terms of numbers feels both odd and incredible. 

So this last little week of 24 I will savor it and let it be really real to me!

25. 

This morning I read through my old birthday captions. 23 in particular stood out to me. 

On my 23nd birthday I wrote about feeling like I was taking a leap of faith and risking every comfort I had for the sake of know God has better for me. 

I teared up reading that post because I remember how hard that was for me. I remember the work and the tears and the fear that was trusting in that way. 

I am SO thankful I did risk though because today I sit here writing my 25th birthday post with tears in my eyes and a very full heart because of that leap of faith little 23 year old Karli took. 

I live in the harvest of all her hard work today. I get to be celebrating this day and all that is to come because of that way she faced her fears and decided I was worth it. 

Never underestimate the power of making a change in your life or taking a risk that you aren’t sure will work out in your favor. 2 years post faith leap I can look back at her and say you did well! 

This year I’m thankful for the fact that I can even write this caption (remember when I couldn’t do that), to be engaged and planning my dream wedding, & to have friends and family with me each step of the way.   Cheers to 25, to promises fulfilled, to dreams come true, & to all the risks it took to get here!

2023. 

Honesty hour. 

The past 5 days have been tear soaked & hard. 

This birthday was one of the best and worst. I cried for a lot of reasons almost the whole day. 

With puffy eyes I found myself letting my fiancé and his family into a place that I’ve never had nurtured before and was met with so much love. I had a real family dinner for the very first time on my birthday & it was best gift I’ve probably ever received. 

From really hard days to harder relationship dynamics to challenged faith — it’s been a week.

I’m learning that no matter how much I plan or pray or will something to happen it never works out how I thought and it always pans out far better than I could have imagined. 

So for the birthdays lost to dysfunctional family members, to the puppies we were promised and not given, to the relationships lost that once meant the world to us — I believe God is still on the throne. 

I believe my God is a good father who’s in the business of redemption and reconciliation. 

To every broken promise, neglected memory, & painful part— He sees it. 

Though I don’t see the other end of his promise just yet I know he isn’t done. 

2023 is only just the beginning.

I’m so lucky & everything just works out for me. 

This last week I’ve been saying that on repeat & no, nothing has changed in the world around me but I do feel a shift.

I’m gonna be brutally honest — the first week of this year I spent in my negative era. I was hurt, mad, & sad. 

It’s pretty wild though because through letting myself access those emotions & not try to rush out of them I got to receive love from those around me. 

Instead of saying I was fine I chose to be honest and say I’m not fine. Instead of pushing through and forcing myself to get over it I let it happen. 

Don’t get me wrong, it sucked and wasn’t easy but for the first time maybe ever I didn’t have to heal myself, control myself, or be the only one with compassion for myself. 

I received. 

I let those around me see me and love me even when I wasn’t at my best & the very best part is that not a single one left, got mad, told me to get over it, or told me that I’m too much. 

So you know what I am so lucky and everything does work out for me. 

Not because life is perfect but because I have the very best people in my life & I’m learning how to really accept their love.

Don’t save the candles. 

I was listening to an episode of @thick.and.thin.podcast by @katybellotte about this recently & was so inspired. 

This year I had 3 cakes, 3 mini bday shindigs, 3 moments of celebration for the turning of a page. 

It’s ironic because as I’ve shared in other birthday posts this birthday was particularly hard. 

As I was listening to that podcast episode it dawned on me that maybe that’s the point. 

Maybe it’s not ironic at all. Maybe the point it so be present in each moment - for better or worse. 

Let yourself cry when things are sad or hard. Let yourself laugh when things are good and easy. 

And not save the your emotions for only to the good days. Maybe it’s actually ideal to have hard days that are met with good people and celebration to show that we aren’t made for one type of emotion. 

Here is the piece she quoted in the podcast that got me: 

“Someone asked me the other day if I had my life to live over would I change anything.

My answer was no, but then I thought about it and changed my mind.

If I had my life to live over again…

I would have burnt the pink candle that was sculptured like a rose before it melted while being stored.” 

I urge you to read the full piece but for now let that sink in.

My new bestie 🫶🏼

I can’t tell you how much this little bundle of joy has changed my life and we are only on week one. 

My entire life I wanted a dog but because I grew up in a 2 house family I was never able to have one of my own. 

When Michael and I started talking marriage and a life together we started looking at pups to add to our family. We tried 2 times to buy a dog and both times left heartbroken and puppy-less but I guess third time really is a charm. 

Michael found Maggie online and I was super hesitant to get her because of the last 2 times we got rejected and it all felt too fresh but I reluctantly went and the second we saw her she ran up to us like she knew we were hers and it was absolutely mutual. The next day we drove back and picked her up and now she is ours! 

The first week is exhausting and a lot but worth every single second! She is the absolute best, cutest, & happiest little bundle of joy we’ve ever met and I couldn’t be more thankful for her. 

This experience taught me that the wait is worth it because it prepares you for the perfect one. From dating to puppies to moving to whatever else you’re waiting for — once you’re on the other side you’ll be so thankful you waited for the right one!

Not growing up with super caring or nurturing parents can make you question if you just weren’t born with the gene or don’t have it in ya but one second with this dog in my arms and years of those questions were answered. 

No matter the upbringing, trauma, past experiences, YOU are capable of giving and getting real # love. 

As someone who’s asked all the questions and lived with the doubt… please don’t waste another second questioning yourself & buy a dang dog if that’s what it takes to finally believe it. 

Also seeing Michael and my partnership grow through this gets me so excited for our future and babies and more dogs and houses and just doing it all! Eep!

Overall, Maggie has completely changed my life in unimaginable ways and I couldn’t imagine a life without her now!

To do. 

Lots on the to do list lately. I’d be lying if I said I wasn’t an an absolute stress case sometimes.

My calendar is booked out almost 10 hours each day organizing one roommate in and one roommate out (very happy but time consuming & extremely exhausting), planning a wedding on an entirely different time zone, half owning a dog that lives an hour away, running my own small business & the over all stress of schedule tetris of family/bridal party/friends/housing stuff… the list never ends. 

Each thing in my life is an absolute gift that I wouldn’t change for the world but all at once can be overwhelming for sure. 

I’m seeing I have a bigger capacity than I thought but that my capacity does have limits so boundaries paired with clear communication during this time are a must!

I’m definitely overextended so prayers/encouragements are appreciated & grace as someone in my life wanting my time is very needed.

Movement. 

I decided to change my life around and though it won’t look how I expected I know it will turn out for good. 

I put in my 30 days notice for my room rental and started packing boxes. 

This choice for change brought up so much in me. 

I looked back on my younger self and how often she risked. She had an ability to go for whatever she felt was right without hesitance. 

I don’t see that trait in myself anymore. Instead I see a lot of fear around risking.

I question why that is the case and I honestly have no conclusions haha but I think that’s the point… 

Even though I don’t have the full picture I’m taking a risk. Even though I don’t know what will come of it I’m trying a new route. Even though I’m pretty unsure I’m getting out of my comfort zone. 

Without seeing the full picture I trust that I have a God who makes all things good on my side.

Another. 

Today I woke up at 5am to sit in the silence with a cup of coffee in hand and a journal out. 

I drew my attention to my breath, expanding my inhale and exhale. The world melted away so that I could be fully present in my mind, body, & spirit. 

From that place of stillness I wrote about a present situation and asked God if I’m being emotional/irrational. 

His response was so gentle, so still, so tender — there is a difference between an emotional and irrational choice. To equate those two things would be a disservice to what God wants to do. 

I found so much peace in that answer. What if God wanted us to be fully present in our emotions as we endeavor into hard conversations and circumstances? 

What if having emotions actually helped the situation instead of a cold closed off approach. 

Another hard situation clarified in a single moment in His presence.

Safety net. 

The honest truth is that I’ve been going THROUGH it… 

work, friends, money, moving, family, & fears all blowing up/all at once. 

For the first time in a very long time work has surprisingly not been my safety net & has lead me to a lot of hard questions. 

It’s felt overwhelming and brought me to tears quite a few times in the past week. 

For about 4 years now I’ve run my own business and balanced a million roles in one day. I’ve learned a lot of lessons and transformed as a human because of the constant stretching it requires to do that.

In hard times I used to dive into work to be my sense of security & I often found the sense of being spread to my thinnest points in work life invigorating. 

Today I feel a new way though. I feel worn out, tired of being a million different roles, & divided in far too many places. 

I feel a craving for simplicity & a sort of narrowing down. 

My prayers are that God opens a door to the best case solution and that I feel that same gut feeling I felt the day I started my own company. 

Tonight I honestly shared all this with the man in these photos & instead of telling me I’m weak or that I should give up or work harder I was told that I’m supported in any direction I choose. 

I’m sobbing even writing that because I get to have this guy by my side having these conversations for the rest of my days. 

Cheers to whatever comes next because I have someone on my side through it all.

A moment of honesty, 

The choices you go through as a bride when it comes to the guest list are excruciating and there’s no way to sugar coat that. 

In the beginning I approached it as a people pleaser making my self stretch as thin as I possibly could to make everyone happy. A month or two in I realized this was happening and I asked myself if that was how I wanted it to go. 

For the first time maybe ever I chose to ask myself what I wanted instead of what others wanted from me & it absolutely changed everything. We Marie Kondo’d the guest list and made sure each and every person invited sparked joy. 

We set requirements of the type of character we wanted around us for this enormous moment. We required that the people who were invited were kind, supportive, and had the ability to put us first for this moment in time. 

I’ve never been happier that I made that stop, asked that question, & had each person we had by our side for the happiest day of our lives. 

Life is absolutely what you make it & who you fill it with. When it comes to important moments there simply isn’t room for people who make it about themselves, take from your joy, or can’t celebrate you. 

And the best part is that it’s mutual. I look at each person here and think about what a privilege it will be to be beside them through their victories!

little moments from our day - part one 

This moment was just after the ceremony. 

We had to do these photos after the ceremony because the florals arrived basically the second I walked down the aisle. 

Remember how I mentioned that this day was the most imperfectly perfect day? 

The flowers were the main part of my vision when it came to wedding planning. I wrapped my whole design concept around cascading & romantic feeling floral design. I spent months planning, spam emailing my INCREDIBLE florist, & dreaming about them.

All those months of planning only to find out just hours before the ceremony that I had put the wrong date on our contract and the florist had planned to come the day after my wedding day. 

My coordinator got a call right after our final run through and we were looped into all this with only a few hours to make a game plan. I pulled on my sister’s past floral skills and told the florist that we would work with whatever she could do. 

Thank God she was such a sweetheart and was even willing to make it work. She absolutely could have said it was my mess up and left us in the dust. She didn’t, in fact she went out of her way to still make it happen. 

My florist’s husband left his job to rush her to our venue and my coordinator’s husband rushed to a flower farm an hour away to get flowers.

This was one of the rare moments our DJ got right. 

The most imperfectly perfect day of my life was mostly due to this DJ and all of us who were there are already laughing while reading this. 

When I booked this venue I was given a small list of vendors in the small French countryside town. There was one DJ listed. 

I thought, how bad can a DJ mess up? (Having 3 audio techs at the wedding was also reassuring that it would be fine). 

Brides, please hire me to plan for you so you don’t have to go through this. I am now dedicating my life to making sure no bride ever goes through a moment like this. 

First, I noticed the bridal party walked to a different song than I chose, weird but not the end of the world. Then I listened for my song to start telling me it’s time to walk down the aisle. 

Instead of hearing the song I picked, spent months listening to in preparation of this momentous moment, & had such a significant attachment to I heard “let’s call it forever” by @barkmarlow (not a bad song choice but I had it picked for our exit song). 

The whole bridal party giggled and I spent the whole time walking down the aisle laughing. I looked at all my friends smiling and we all just took it for what it was. 

No, it wasn’t what I planned. It wasn’t the type of moment that makes you cry or get goose bumps like I thought it would have been. But it was ours and we all found so much joy in the fact that it was imperfect.

After the ceremony wrapped Michael and I began to walk out and no music played the entire time we all walked out no music played. Again we all laughed and made it our moment despite it being the opposite of what I had planned. 

After the night was near an end we put on our song (thankfully this one was right) and danced. The song sang the following words.. 

“All I know is the simple truth
I like watching the days go by with you” 

though it was imperfect it was ours.

When I was younger I didn’t grow up with summer vacations in Europe or even knowing I could dream of that. 

As I grew up I found a little part of my tucked away wanting adventure and exploration. I let that part of myself test the waters when I decided to move to Norway at 17 and then again at 18 when I moved to Greece. 

That time in my life felt like I could do anything. Not because I was naive but because I just witnessed myself do something I deemed impossible.

Over the years of moving back home, growing up, working & settling down I felt that wonder be put on the back burner. 

I found myself saying that I don’t know if I’m even capable of taking big risks anymore. A quality I used to find so core to my identity. I felt like I lost a part of myself in the growing up process. 

At the start of this year I set my eyes on taking risks again. I told myself that I wasn’t going to lock that part of myself up anymore. That feeling of excitement about potential and wonder would be my lead again. 

I could not be happier that I made that intentional choice because in the past 8 months I’ve lived the life I wanted to live. I’ve traveled, had my dream wedding, made changes, & seen potential become reality again. 

For all of those who might feel scared of the what if’s… you don’t get to live in this exact moment ever again so don’t waste a single second. You were made to live BIG, take risks, fail, succeed, & keep getting back up!

How a trip to Paris taught me to live in the moment… 

I’ve spent a lot of time reliving my trip to France. I’ve mainly been reflecting on the way I felt while I was there.

The juxtaposition of our pace of life to my time in Europe makes me think about how many once in a life time experiences I’ve gotten to live in my lifetime and just how much I missed the actual moments they happened in. 

I can now acknowledge how rare it is to move across the world at 17, start a business that actually lasts 4 years, or find people that will stand by you thick and thin at such a young age. 

When I look at my 25 years on this planet and think of all the unbelievable experiences I’ve had it makes me want to soak up each moment I have in front of me. 

I want to make memories while I’m 25 that I can tell my kids about. I want to have the kinds of experiences that I’ll wish to relive years from now. I want to grow old and gray with a smile on my face because I truly lived. 

I’ve spent so many years in planning mode for what will come, but I see now that part of growing up and maturing is learning to live in the present. 

I’m not one to preach reckless abandonment for the sake of youth, so don’t misunderstand me. 

I’m simply hinting that I won’t get to be 25 ever again. I won’t get to be in this place with these people experiencing this moment ever again. Realizing that really makes you want to be present and enjoy the experiences of now.

Date night photo dump 🫶🏼

Before getting married we were the busiest couple on earth. We juggled running my own business, planning a wedding, Michael’s school schedule, Michael working endless summer jobs on top of a full time job, & the typical life to do list. 

Our date nights were going to the grocery store or folding laundry together. I loved every second of our time together then but had no idea what could be. 

After weeks in Europe around our wedding I learned a major relationship lesson. 

TIME SPENT TOGETHER IS KEY! 

No that doesn’t need to be a whole day extravaganza but it does need to be in the calendar. Setting an immovable priority for your relationship above all else changes the game. 

I never knew I would ever say anything like that because the friendship was so core to our relationship before. I required so little, until I got married and spent time doing things we love and investing in new experiences together. 

Seeing how much we thrive when we take that intentional time has changed my perspective entirely! Now I even prioritize date nights with my friends and family too! 

It’s taught me to really savor time spent with people you love in general.

Since I promised myself & I hold a lot of value for my promises… 

The last 3 months of my life have been some of the hardest I have ever gone through. I say that not negating that there have been some really amazing moments too, I do not live in a tunnel vision vacuum where only one or the other can be true but for the sake of trying to share a real story - things have been hard as much as they’ve been good. 

I think growing up as a Christian in the church you’re raised to believe that marriage is the end goal where life begins. There’s a subconscious belief instilled in you that that says on the other side of I do is when real life begins. 

In some senses that’s true - life does in a way start over and everything is changed. There’s no going backwards and the way you think, live, choose etc. all changes. 

In another way that’s wrong because as much as the starting over is true you are still very much yourself & all the baggage that existed is still present. Then, on top of that you have a second person to think about who still has all their old baggage too. 

It would be wrong for me to come here saying that I’m transparent and vulnerable and not share that marriage by far has been the biggest and hardest challenge I have ever faced. 

Some might not know but that’s saying a lot since my mere 25 years on this planet have not exactly been a breeze. This is me saying that these small 3 months have been harder than raising myself all through childhood and harder than growing a business at the young age of 20 (and those are just the things that I’m able to share here). 

So what have I come out of these months learning? I’ve learned that marriage is the most intense refining process you will ever go through.

All this to say, I wouldn’t take it back or change it but I would tell the single person I used to be that no ring on my finger or signed government document will solve the things I have lying under the surface & having a partner to face them with isn’t always an easier route but that I’m strong and capable of more than I think.

If you’re thinking ‘how the heck did she get a Tesla’ know that I’m right there with ya…

The answer is that God just simply outdoes himself every time! 

The story behind my new ride begins just over a month ago when I had an extremely hard week in my marriage and what felt like every other area of my life. I left the house after work to process it all through a walk on the beach. On my way back, just one exit away from my house, I got in a car accident. 

Upon getting my car evaluated I was told that the crash hit some important wires that would be over 20k to fix so my car would have to be claimed totaled.

I felt the weight of everything I had been going through for the past months hit me and I broke down crying. I told God how I wished I had parents that would come to my rescue in moments like this and that the feeling of having to constantly fix everything on my own felt devastating. 

In that moment I felt like God said, if you will let me I would love to take care of this for you. It felt dumb to say “god will just solve this for me” but truthfully that’s what my heart wanted. I didn’t want to have to solve this problem on my own. 

After what felt like the longest month of my life with no car, trapped in my room all alone, and my mental health deteriorating I got news that the settlement from my totaled car came through and was more than enough to pay for a car that was far nicer than the one I had before. 

So that same day I bought the car I now have with basically no money out of my own bank account. 

All this to say, let God take care of it. Whatever your ‘it’ is… you don’t have to do it on your own, no matter how many years you’ve spent doing it what way. 

And no matter how hard things are they always work themselves out with time. Sometimes you go through fire to come out refined first but even in that God’s right there in the fire with you.

As the clocked turned to midnight on January 1st this year I just decided that things internally would be different this year. I chose to look at things through a different lens and to touch base with that part of myself that got lost.

That is what keeps me going.
